<DOC><DOCNO> AP881216-0230 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 0114EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   12-16 0506</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0528</SECOND><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Platinum prices tumbled in major world markets oneday after Ford Motor Co. announced a pilot program to eliminate theprecious metal from the pollution control devices used in many cars.   Ford revealed no details of the device but said it would resultin a significant cost reduction. Spokesman Bill Peacock would notsay whether any savings would be passed along to car buyers.   Spot platinum on the spot market closed Thursday at $531.90 atroy ounce at the New York Mercantile Exchange, down $34.10 an ouncefrom Wednesday's close.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The agency regulating nationally charteredbanks ordered its examiners to look for banks that have taken toobig a chunk of the risky, but lucrative, business of financingleveraged buyouts.   The Office of the Comptroller of the Currency, which regulatesabout 4,400 of the nation's 14,000 commercial banks, issued a set ofguidelines Thursday for banks and government examiners to determinewhether a bank's safety is endangered by involvement in the buyouts,commonly known as LBOs.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The number of U.S. business failures fell by 6.3percent during the first three quarters of this year, the bestperformance in nearly a decade, according to a private survey.   The number of business failures fell to 44,793 from 47,794 in thefirst nine months of 1987, the report by Dun andamp; Bradstreet Corp. saidThursday.   The decline was attributed largely to ``decreases in the levelsof failures in the oil and agricultural states.''</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Lorimar Telepictures Inc. has agreed to sell itsPuerto Rican television broadcast interests, removing an obstacle tothe entertainment company's proposed sale to Warner CommunicationsInc.   Lorimar's interest in the two stations as well as its ownershipof a third station in Pittsburgh has prevented the Culver City,Calif.,-based company from moving ahead on its agreement to beacquired by Warner in an exchange of stock and debt that has beenvalued at about $1.2 billion.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Four former chiefs of the Federal HighwayAdministration say they oppose proposals to raise the tax ongasoline to reduce the budget deficit.   Such a change, they said Thursday, would fall unfairly on thepoor, worsen inflation, deprive the states of a revenue source andfurther delay improvement of the nation's deteriorating highways andbridges.   They spoke at a news conference sponsored by The Road InformationProgram, an advocacy group financed by energy, insurance, automobileand highway-construction companies.</TEXT><DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   International Business Machines Corp.decided to extend a 1984 antitrust settlement that requires thecomputer giant to give certain technical information to competitorsin Europe.   The U.S. company and the European Economic Community said in astatement Thursday that the accord ``has come to serve as aneffective vehicle'' for resolving questions on how competingmachines can be hooked up to IBM equipment.   The 1984 settlement suspended a 4-year antitrust case brought bythe 12-nation trading bloc against IBM.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>